    "body": "## Problem\n\nWhen using tree-sitter language injection, the host language's highlights can \"bleed through\" to the injected language because both have the same default priority (100).\n\n### Concrete Example\n\nInjecting markdown into a bash heredoc:\n\n```bash\ncat <<'MARKDOWN'\nThis is **bold** text.\nMARKDOWN\n```\n\n- `@string.bash`: priority 100, `fg=green`\n- `@markup.strong` (markdown): priority 100, `fg=none` (only `bold` attribute)\n\nSince `@markup.strong` has no `fg`, the `@string.bash` green color shows through, even though the child tree renders after the parent (#32619).\n\n### Desired Behavior\n\nI want to lower `@string.bash` priority to 50 **only for `heredoc_body`**, so injected highlights take precedence:\n\n```\ninjected language  ─── priority 100\n@string.bash       ─── priority 50\n```\n\n### Current Limitation\n\n**Cannot modify an existing capture's priority via `; extends`.**\n\nThis does NOT work:\n```scm\n; extends\n((heredoc_body) @string (#set! priority 50))\n```\n\nThis **adds** a new capture rather than modifying the existing one. Both the original (priority 100) and the new (priority 50) coexist.\n\n### Current Workaround\n\nThe only solution is to:\n1. Read the entire `bash/highlights.scm`\n2. Modify it with regex\n3. Replace with `vim.treesitter.query.set()`\n\nThis is fragile and breaks when upstream queries change.\n\n## Proposal\n\nAdd a mechanism to **override a specific capture's metadata** (like priority) without redefining the entire pattern. Possible approaches:\n\n1. **`; overrides` modeline** - captures in this file replace matching captures in base queries\n2. **`#override!` directive** - explicitly mark a capture as overriding an existing one\n3. **Pattern matching by capture name** - if an `; extends` file captures the same node with the same capture name, merge/replace metadata\n\n## Related\n\n- #23373 - `; override` for full query replacement (closed, resolved by runtimepath precedence)\n- #31853 - Automatic priority offset for injection trees (closed)\n- #32619 - Child tree renders after parent at same priority (merged, doesn't solve fg bleeding)\n- nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter#7816 - Discussion about this limitation\n",
